title: Episode 27 – Jennifer Menke – President, Regenerative Earth
subtitle: Sarah Arao Mantle of Hope- Thank You Video to the Y on Earth Community for GoFundMe Campaign Support
full_transcript:
[8.4s - 13.8s]: Welcome to the Y on Earth communities stewardship and sustainability podcast series.

[14.8s - 17.9s]: Today we have with us Jennifer Menki, hi Jennifer.

[18.4s - 18.6s]: Hi.

[19.1s - 19.9s]: Great to have you here.

[20.2s - 23.4s]: Yes, thank you so much for inviting me on to this podcast.

[23.9s - 24.3s]: Absolutely.

[25.3s - 36.3s]: Jennifer is the project director of regenerative economy lab and founder and president of regenerative earth of 501c3 nonprofit corporation.

[37.0s - 47.1s]: In 2015 she was nominated as an emerging global leader by the Academy for Systems Change and reside as a fellow of the organization.

[48.2s - 65.3s]: Jennifer has been managing a project in the OSAP Peninsula Costa Rica for the past three years facilitating local communities and governments to develop and implement a regenerative rainforest economy in which the community ecosystem and economy all thrive.

[66.3s - 77.5s]: Jennifer's community resource mapping and facilitation techniques translate to diverse projects around the world facilitating the rapid evolution of sustainable economic models.

[78.0s - 88.7s]: She also curates nature-based emerging retreat experiences for executives, investors and leaders in their field. Welcome Jennifer.

[89.4s - 90.5s]: Thank you.

[91.5s - 118.0s]: I am so excited to chat with you today and to talk with you about the various threads that you've woven together in your personal life and your professional life and the ways in which you're able to bring so much value to executives and investors, others who are doing their part to help heal our planet and to help create restorative and regenerative systems.

[118.0s - 133.4s]: I want to ask before we get into some of the technical sides of this, how did this get started for you? I know that this is a journey you've been on for a number of years. How did that get rolling?

[134.4s - 138.3s]: The work specifically in the OSAP and the research.

[139.9s - 159.5s]: Since I was 22, I've been studying and been mentored by different Indigenous elders and spiritual leaders and elders in guiding retreats and learning how to guide retreats.

[160.6s - 169.8s]: Since that was about 15 years ago, I started on that path and every winter I would do retreats on in Baja.

[170.3s - 181.5s]: The Baja had host started getting developed where we would put people out on nature solos and so we looked for their soil to find a place for the wintertime for these retreats.

[183.9s - 190.6s]: The best option we saw was the host was the best option we saw. We went down there and discovered shortly after the OSAP and INFLU.

[191.4s - 201.4s]: We decided to do the retreats on the OSAP and INFLU because it has one of the largest or longest stretches of low-lying rainforests left in the world.

[201.4s - 222.2s]: It's fairly undeveloped. It's the wild west of Costa Rica and it makes a really conducive place for the retreats in nature where people can experience that first being untouched wilderness and in the case of the OSAP, that primary rainforest.

[222.2s - 251.7s]: We went down there and started doing retreats there and I just fell in love with the rainforest and also saw the needs that were being expressed by the community around needing help with supporting people's livelihoods, as well as protecting the rainforest because it was on the map for development just coming in.

[252.6s - 264.5s]: It's not that critical of temperature and time where people know about the OSAP, they're attracted to it and there's more potential development coming in.

[265.4s - 279.4s]: There needs to be the plans, the structure and place to really protect the rainforests, protect the people and the culture and just nurture it.

[279.4s - 300.2s]: I understand that that INFLU, which is on the very southwest part of Costa Rica, is one of the most biodiverse places on the planet and it's an incredible treasure in terms of genetic diversity with all those different species there.

[300.2s - 322.5s]: That means on the one hand it's a really important place to be protecting and on the other hand it's an incredibly powerful place to bring executives and professionals to have this deeper connection with nature and with a primitive old growth rainforest environment.

[322.5s - 336.5s]: This is interesting because a lot of these executives are spending much of their time in boardrooms and front of computers with spreadsheets and reports and often office buildings in the middle of cities is a very different experience for them.

[336.7s - 345.8s]: I'm curious, what do you observe when you're leading these retreats and these sessions with folks who are coming down from that kind of environment?

[346.8s - 361.8s]: Yeah, I mean it's a great question because we definitely get people that come on this retreat in Costa Rica who have never been camping before in their life and then they're trying to actively spend the night in the rainforest for a seven-night alone.

[390.4s - 415.3s]: And so part of the awareness training that we put people through is helping people to deeply relax and cultivate a level of presence and awareness and when that happens and when you're in solitude practicing that, when naturally unfolds is the heart starts to open up and connection begins to happen and it's not a mental connection.
